{
  "doc_id": "56944",
  "text": "Much work has been done also in the area of spatial logic [CITATION_1] , yet focussing more on expressivity and decidability, often in continuous space. Less attention has been placed on more practical aspects, like model checking routines in discrete space. An exception is the work of some of the authors [CITATION_2] , in which the Spatial Logic for Closure Spaces (SLCS) is proposed for a discrete and topological notion of space, based on closure spaces [CITATION_3] . First applications of that work in the context of smart transportation can be found in [CITATION_4] . Another spatial logic equipped with practical model checking algorithms, and with learning procedures, is that of [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , in which spatial properties are expressed using ideas from image processing, namely quad trees. This allows one to capture very complex spatial structures, but at the price of a complex formulation of spatial properties, which are in practice only learned from some template image.",
